Data summary

Here, we will practice the observation of data using Fisher's iris data set as an example.
This dataset is for 50 species of irises (setosa, versicolor, virginica) for each of 3 species.
The length and width of the calyx (seal) and the length and width of the petal (Petal) are stored in this order as feature quantities.
All units are cm.
In this exercise, we would like to look at the correspondence between these four features and the types of irises.
https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1111/j.1469-1809.1936.tb02137.x
For more information on the dataset, please see Wikipedia Iris dataset.
The image is also a quote from this article. From left to right are setosa, versicolor and virginica.
You can also follow the original data paper from this article.
Edgar Anderson (1936). "The species problem in Iris". Annals of the Missouri Botanical Garden. 23 (3): 457–509. doi:10.2307/2394164. JSTOR 2394164.
In this paper, the figure ( Fig.8 ) which part was measured is described.
R. A. Fisher (1936). "The use of multiple measurements in taxonomic problems". Annals of Eugenics. 7 (2): 179–188. doi:10.1111/j.1469-1809.1936.tb02137.x. hdl:2440/15227
This paper contains a numerical table.

Observe raw data

Let's observe the data by calculating statistics and writing graphs.

Observation by parallel plot

This time, one data consists of four numbers.
There are two ways to observe them. One is a parallel plot.
parallelplot(meas, 'GroupData', species, 'Color', {'red', 'green', 'blue'});
There are 150 broken lines, which is the number of data. Corresponds to four numbers.
The data of versicolor and virginica are relatively similar, and it seems that only setosa is separated.
Click once on the image in the live editor. After that, trace the image with the mouse.
The line the cursor is on is highlighted and you can see the detailed values.
Click the arrow icon in the upper right corner to display the graph in a new window.

Observation by glyph plot

The other is a glyph plot.
glyphplot(meas);
The feature quantity is displayed as a polygon for each data.
This time, the data is made up of four numbers, so it is a square.
From the contents of the species variable, it is known that 1 to 50 are setosa , 51 to 100 are versicolor , and 101 to 150 are virginica .
The rectangle is larger in the order of setosa , versicolor , and virginica .
Compared to the differences between the varieties, the variability within the varieties (individual differences) seems to be relatively small.。

Observation by histogram

First, let's take a histogram of the features of the data.
Only one example is shown here, but let's check the other three feature quantities.
figure;
histogram(meas(:,1))
xlabel("Sepal length");
histogram is a command for literally calculating and displaying a histogram.

Observation by plotting feature pairs

By the way, the iris data set this time was about three varieties. Let's take a look at the relationship between the feature amount and the varieties related to sepal.
figure;
gscatter(meas(:,1), meas(:,2), species, 'rgb');
xlabel('Sepal length');
ylabel('Sepal width');
gscatter is, the first 3 in each group as given by the argument, 2 is a comment that displays the dimensional data.
'Rgb' given as an argument of the command is an option to specify the colors to be plotted in the order of appearance of groups as "red, green, blue".
From this figure, it can be seen that the length and width of the sepals are likely to be related to each other. In other words, it seems that each cultivar has the property that the length of the sepal is large and the width is wide.
On the other hand, the overall correlation across varieties seems low.
Also from this figure, it can be said that versicolor and virginica have relatively similar data, and only setosa is separated.
Now , let's visualize the petals with gscatter .
The commands are shown below, but if you can, think for yourself.
figure;
gscatter(meas(:,3), meas(:,4), species, 'rgb');
xlabel('Petal length');
ylabel('Petal width');
In addition to the correlation for each variety, there seems to be an overall correlation.
In this figure, versicolor and virginica are also relatively clumped.
Furthermore, following the previous figure, setosa is very divided.
As an exercise, try plotting other feature pairs, including the combination of sepals and petals.

About correspondence between data and the real thing

From the observation of the data, we can conclude that versicolor and virginica are similar and only setosa is different.
Again, let's return to the top of this page and compare the three photos from Wikipeida .
It's true that setosa is very different from others, and versicolor and virginica are similar.
When analyzing data, I think it's important to not only look at the numbers that have been converted into data, but to touch " information on site " as much as possible . In this example, I want to go directly to the iris field, but unfortunately I can't do that, so I looked at the photos and confirmed that the features were convincing.
Please check other images of the iris yourself using internet.
Well, I can say that only setosa is out of the company.
Sometimes when you're having trouble analyzing your data, some hints may be hidden in how you measure it. The unit system is also important.

Observation by scatter plot

Now, the plots of feature pairs that we have seen so far can actually be viewed together with the following command.
gplotmatrix(meas, [], species, 'rgb');
In this plot, the graphs are arranged in tiles with the number of features x the number of features ( 4x4 in this case ).
On the diagonal, a histogram for each group for each feature,
On the non-diagonal, there are plots for each feature pair.
We knew from the observations so far, but looking at this figure again,

Apply dimensional compression method/dimension reduction

Apply principal component analysis

Principal component analysis is a method in which the coordinate axes are re-established based on how the data spread.
This method does not use class labels, but calculates new axes only from the features.
Therefore, it basically works effectively when there is a relationship between how the features spread and the class boundaries.
To put it the other way around, it doesn't work well when the direction in which the data is spread has little to do with the class label.
To put it a little more concretely assuming the data of this time, principal component analysis is a method that is suitable when the variation in the characteristic amount between varieties is larger than the variation in the characteristic amount within the variety.
(Of course, I think that it can be used if it is not so, but the basic story is.)
I confirmed that it seems to be okay in the figure above, so let's apply it immediately.
[coeff, score, latent, ~, ~, mu] = pca(meas);
For detailed specifications, refer to the manual with the doc command.
coeff is the return value for the new basis, score is the coordinate of each data on these basis, the eigenvalues of the variance-covariance matrix, and mu is the mean vector.
You may want to check the number of elements in each data.
Plotting the results of the principal component analysis gives:
figure;
gscatter(score(:,1), score(:,2), species, 'rgb');
xlabel('PC1');
ylabel('PC2');
If this axis is adopted, it will be possible to divide it into roughly different parts. You can see the contribution of each axis by checking the variable latent . This is the variable that corresponds to the eigenvalues of the covariance matrix.
latent
latent = 4×1
4.2282 0.2427 0.0782 0.0238
Let's fix it in the form of cumulative contribution rate.
cumsum(latent)/sum(latent)
ans = 4×1
0.9246 0.9777 0.9948 1.0000
It seems to be 97% up to 2 axes . It seems that the data can be divided in two dimensions.
You can see the mean of the principal component analysis with the variable mu and the new basis of the principal component with coeff.
mu
 
coeff(:,1)
coeff(:,2)
The new first axis seems to be looking at variables other than sepal width.
Certainly, from the histogram we saw with gplotmatirx , the width of the septum was not very effective.

Application of tSNE

Although it is not the subject of this time, there is a method called tSNE that is often used as a visualization method, so let's introduce only how to use it.
It is also a method that supports nonlinearity, but new data cannot be mapped to the same space.
See the manual in doc for details.
Y = tsne(meas);
figure;
gscatter(Y(:,1), Y(:,2), species, 'rgb');
The results were exactly the same as our previous findings.
